{"cursor":"30397","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":":This article is about incommensurability in the philosophy of science. For\nother senses of this word, see [[commensurability]].\n\n'Commensurability' (contrast with 'incommensurability') is a concept in the\nphilosophy of science. Scientific theories are described as commensurable if one\ncan compare them to determine which is more accurate; if theories are\nincommensurable, there is no way in which one can compare them to each other in\norder to determine which is more accurate. '' by Rodin.]]\n","linknr":376,"url":"Commensurability_(philosophy_of_science)","recorded":1362564839,"links":25,"instances":["geometry","research","psychology","geometry","philosopher"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Philosophy of science"],"headings":["Thesis","Perspectives","Notes","Bibliography","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg/40px-Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Auguste_Rodin_-_Grubleren_2005-02.jpg/250px-Auguste_Rodin_-_Grubleren_2005-02.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["variable","research"],["square","geometry"],["side","geometry"],["donald_davidson","philosopher"],["assimilation","psychology"]],"members":["side","variable","assimilation","square","donald_davidson"],"related":["Philosophy_of_science","Scientific_theories","Auguste_Rodin","Thomas_Kuhn","Paul_Feyerabend","Concept","Mathematics","Variable_(research)","Diagonal","Square_(geometry)","Side_(geometry)","Theories","Thesis","Received_view_of_theories","Scientific_knowledge","Standard_language","Empiricism","Karl_Popper","Rationality"